</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 The letter is docketed by GW Jno. Ballendines Letter &amp; Papersrespectg the Iron he delivd short in 1760, and also in GWs hand are figures calculating the amount of the shortage of iron delivered to him.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Ballendines earlier letter is <span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from 'printed below' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-10]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">included</span> as an <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0277-0002" class="document">enclosure</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>In a deposition dated 23 Jan. 1760 (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>), Robert Grimmitt, Ballendines overseer, claimed that he was ordered by Mr John Ballendine at the occoquan forge, to send Down to the landing a ton of Bar Iron for Coln. washington to be put on board a flatt Belonging to Messrs Carlyle &amp; Dalton with a ton before Delivered to the sd flatt &amp; weighed and Rect Given by the
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-06-02-pb-0478">[478]</span>
Skipper of the sd flatt Derby pendergrass which said two tons of Iron I understood was for Coln. washington But the River being froze up, the sd Iron was Delvered to two waggons to Go up by Land, &amp; Do further Certifie that the Last ton of Iron was Delvered to the Carter out of the Iron house by me and was not weighed But Immagind it was weighed by the forge man, as it lay up in the Corner of the house; &amp; so sent it to the Landing for the flatt to take in; which was landed at The new furn[a]ce warf, where the flatt Lay, &amp; was From their taken in By the Dutch wagonners.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0276" class="document">Joseph Stephens to GW, 15 Nov. 1760</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-06-02-0277-0001-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>For earlier correspondence on the shortage in Ballendines iron bars, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0210" class="document">George Johnston to GW</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-06-02-0209" class="document">John Carlyle to GW, both dated 8 Jan. 1760</a>.</p>

</div>
